"Also, several tools allow for selecting the output format ``.vrt`` avoiding "
"the time required to create a unique ``.tif`` raster (after multiprocess), "
"especially useful for large rasters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:340
msgid ""
"How do I perform accuracy assessment and how to design the number of "
"samples?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:342
msgid ""
"Accuracy assessment is described in `this tutorial "
"<https://fromgistors.blogspot.com/2019/09/Accuracy-Assessment-of-Land-Cover-"
"Classification.html>`_ ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:345
msgid ""
"Sample design is required to provide an adequate number of samples for each "
"class, as described in \"Olofsson, et al., 2014. Good practices for "
"estimating area and assessing accuracy of land change. Remote Sensing of "
"Environment, 148, 42 – 57\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:350
msgid ""
"The number of samples (:math:`N`) should be calculated as (Olofsson, et al.,"
" 2014):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:353
msgid ""
"N = ( \\sum_{i=1}^{c} (W_i - S_i) / S_o)^2\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:356
msgid "where:"
msgstr "де:"

#: ../../faq.rst:358
msgid ":math:`W_i` = mapped area proportion of class i;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:359
msgid ":math:`S_i` = standard deviation of stratum i;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:360
msgid ":math:`S_o` = expected standard deviation of overall accuracy;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:361
msgid ":math:`c` = total number of classes;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:363
msgid ""
"To stratify the sample we should conjecture user’s accuracy and standard "
"deviations of strata (Olofsson, et al., 2014). One can hypothesize that "
"user’s accuracy is lower and standard deviations :math:`S_i` is higher for "
"classes having low area proportion, but of course these values should be "
"carefully evaluated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:369
msgid ""
"This requires some conjectures about overall accuracy and user’s accuracy of"
" each class. We should base these conjectures on previous studies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:373
msgid ""
"As starting values, we could assume :math:`S_o = 0.01` and perform a rough "
"accuracy assessment with random samples, and eventually calculate the "
":math:`S_i` to perform the sampling design. Alternatively, one could start "
"with Si = 0.5 for all the classes. Basically the higher is Si, the larger is"
" the number of samples for that class."
msgstr ""

